<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 4:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If27b93016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="Ib978dbb0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Procedure Before the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94ee1e37e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:9.</label.designator><headtext>Initiating Panel proceedings—Form of papers and number of copies</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Papers filed with the Panel must conform to certain formal requirements. <eos/><bos/>In general, these requirements are the same as those of other federal courts. <eos/><bos/>For example, all papers must be filed on 8½ x 11 inch paper.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If27bba106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] Presumably on the grounds of obviousness, the rules no longer expressly require that the paper be white, opaque, and unglazed or that onionskin paper not be used.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If27bba126b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] The Panel Rules no longer require that motions contain numbered paragraphs limited to a single averment, although that form continues to be an clear and convenient way to organize an effective motion.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Under ECF, only a single copy of a paper is filed. <eos/><bos/>In addition, a single courtesy copy of certain pleadings must be sent to the Panel, with the legend &quot;Courtesy Copy—Do Not File&quot; clearly marked on it. <eos/><bos/>If the ECF filing number is known, it should be included. <eos/><bos/>ECF users to file a single copy, and to provide a single courtesy copy by mail within 24 hours. <eos/><bos/>Non-ECF users file the original and one copy at the same time.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If27d40b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] The documents for which the original alone may be filed are generally those that are used in the Clerk&apos;s office but which do not normally need to be circulated to each Panel member.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If27b93016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If27bba106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I5518e4f06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 3.2(a)(iv)</cite.query>&amp;<cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.3" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I5518e4f16b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">3.3(b)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If27bba116b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If27bba126b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> former J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR7.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I551b7d006b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 7.1(c)(iii)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If27d40b06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If27d40b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I552b34706b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 3.2</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If27d40b26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I552b34716b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 3.2(d)</cite.query> requires the courtesy copy of a motion for transfer and its supporting brief, a response to a show cause order, a motion to vacate a conditional transfer order or conditional remand order, any response or reply relating to those pleadings, and the corporate disclosure statement required by <cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR5.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I552b34726b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 5.1</cite.query><cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I552b34736b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">3.2(a)(iv)</cite.query>&amp;<cite.query w-src-number="0304913976" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR3.3" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I552b34746b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">3.3(b)</cite.query>.<eos/><bos/></paratext><paratext>Forms of many of these documents appear in <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANAPPA" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If27d67c06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">Appendix A</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 4:9<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
